<subSubSection id="079E653C534FFF83FEF3834FFAC0FF57" lastPageId="19" lastPageNumber="20" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="4F3B36B7534FFF81FEF3834FFE5FF8CC" blockId="17.[151,1437,1468,2035]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis id="7DF0EAA5534FFF81FEF3834FFE9CF9C8" bold="true" box="[199,308,1612,1638]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Remarks</emphasis>
. The new specimens are very similar to the types of 
<taxonomicName id="88844D34534FFF81FDB0834FFBBBF9C8" authorityName="Lyman" authorityYear="1878" box="[900,1043,1612,1638]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiacanthidae" genus="Ophiacantha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiacanthida" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="cuspidata">
<emphasis id="7DF0EAA5534FFF81FDB0834FFBBBF9C8" box="[900,1043,1612,1638]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">O. cuspidata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
found off 
<collectingCountry id="37937627534FFF81FABC834FFB55F9C8" box="[1160,1277,1612,1638]" name="Saint Helena, Ascension and Tristan da Cunha" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Ascension</collectingCountry>
Is (
<quantity id="887C9B52534FFF81FB1C834FFAD9F9C9" box="[1320,1393,1612,1639]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.81" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" unit="m" value="781.0">781 m</quantity>
) on the Mid-Atlantic Ridge (see 
<bibRefCitation id="2B154B46534FFF81FFE98372FC8AF924" author="Martynov, A. V. &amp; Litvinova, N. M." box="[477,802,1648,1675]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" pagination="76 - 111" refId="ref33866" refString="Martynov, A. V. &amp; Litvinova, N. M. (2008) Deep-water Ophiuroidea of the northern Atlantic with descriptions of three new species and taxonomic remarks on certain genera and species. Marine Biology Research, 4, 76 - 111. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 17451000701840066" type="journal article" year="2008">Martynov &amp; Litvinova 2008</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 7D). They have relatively sparse but long elongate disc spines with thorns diverging at the tip, radial shields marked by a furrow and small exposed distal section, four oral papillae, the outmost widened (sometimes with a groove), pentagonal oral shields, with obtuse proximal margins and a large squarish distal lobe, 8–9 arm spines, and a pointed tentacle scale (
<figureCitation id="D7BF2A32534FFF81FAB883DFFAA0F959" box="[1164,1288,1756,1783]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="18.[151,250,1918,1942]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1894]" captionTargetId="figure-26@18.[151,1436,181,1894]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 6. (A) Ophiacantha veterna, MNHN IE.2009.1562, dorsal outline. (B) MNHN IE.2009.1563, ventral view. (C–E) Ophiosabine cuspidata, MNHN IE.2009.1558, C: dorsal outline, D: dorsal view, E: ventral view. (F) Ophiotreta spectabilis, MNHN IE.2009.1564, dorsal view. (G–H) Ophiolimna bairdi, MNHN IE.2009.1571, G: dorsal and H: ventral views." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6404692" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6404692/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 6C–E</figureCitation>
). The MD 
<specimenCount id="5982FD3E534FFF81FBB583DFFEA4F8B4" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="generic">50 specimens</specimenCount>
measure 
<quantity id="887C9B52534FFF81FF4F8203FE55F8B5" box="[379,509,1792,1819]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.25" metricValueMax="10.5" metricValueMin="6.0" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" unit="mm" value="8.25" valueMax="10.5" valueMin="6.0">6–10.5 mm</quantity>
dd, compared with 
<quantity id="887C9B52534FFF81FCD08203FC8FF8B5" box="[740,807,1792,1819]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.0" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" unit="mm" value="9.0">9 mm</quantity>
for the 
<typeStatus id="903F8815534FFF81FDB18203FC4FF8B4" box="[901,999,1792,1818]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">holotype</typeStatus>
(
<bibRefCitation id="2B154B46534FFF81FDC38203FB24F8B4" author="Lyman, T." box="[1015,1164,1792,1818]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" pagination="1 - 385" refId="ref33271" refString="Lyman, T. (1882) Ophiuroidea. Report on the Scientific Results of the Voyage of the &quot; Challenger &quot; Zoology, 5, 1 - 385 pls. 1 - 48." type="journal article" year="1882">Lyman 1882</bibRefCitation>
). The MD 
<specimenCount id="5982FD3E534FFF81FB378203FA35F8B4" box="[1283,1437,1792,1819]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="generic">50 specimens</specimenCount>
also have small thorns on the distal edge of the dorsal arm plates that were not recorded for the 
<taxonomicName id="88844D34534FFF81FAFE8227FAF2F890" authorityName="Lyman" authorityYear="1878" box="[1226,1370,1828,1854]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiacanthidae" genus="Ophiacantha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiacanthida" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="cuspidata">
<emphasis id="7DF0EAA5534FFF81FAFE8227FAF2F890" box="[1226,1370,1828,1854]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">O. cuspidata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
types but may have been overlooked.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4F3B36B7534FFF83FEF3826EFAC0FF57" blockId="17.[151,1437,1468,2035]" lastBlockId="19.[151,1436,151,249]" lastPageId="19" lastPageNumber="20" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<bibRefCitation id="2B154B46534FFF81FEF3826EFD9DF828" author="Martynov, A. V. &amp; Litvinova, N. M." box="[199,565,1900,1927]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" pagination="76 - 111" refId="ref33866" refString="Martynov, A. V. &amp; Litvinova, N. M. (2008) Deep-water Ophiuroidea of the northern Atlantic with descriptions of three new species and taxonomic remarks on certain genera and species. Marine Biology Research, 4, 76 - 111. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 17451000701840066" type="journal article" year="2008">Martynov and Litvinova (2008)</bibRefCitation>
synonymised the five-armed 
<taxonomicName id="88844D34534FFF81FDBA826FFB89F828" authorityName="Lyman" authorityYear="1878" box="[910,1057,1900,1926]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiacanthidae" genus="Ophiacantha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiacanthida" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="cuspidata">
<emphasis id="7DF0EAA5534FFF81FDBA826FFB89F828" box="[910,1057,1900,1926]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">O. cuspidata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with the six-armed 
<taxonomicName id="88844D34534FFF81FB3A826FFA3DF828" authorityName="Sars" authorityYear="1872" box="[1294,1429,1900,1926]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiacanthidae" genus="Ophiacantha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiacanthida" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="anomala">
<emphasis id="7DF0EAA5534FFF81FB3A826FFA3DF828" box="[1294,1429,1900,1926]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">O. anomala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. They are very similar, and mitochondrial sequence data indicates that for other 
<taxonomicName id="88844D34534FFF81FA1E8293FABFF804" box="[1066,1303,1936,1962]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis id="7DF0EAA5534FFF81FA1E8293FB11F804" box="[1066,1209,1936,1962]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Ophiosabine</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
, such as 
<taxonomicName id="88844D34534FFF81FBB58293FF54F860" authorityName="Mortensen" authorityYear="1936" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiacanthidae" genus="Ophiacantha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiacanthida" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="pentactis">
<emphasis id="7DF0EAA5534FFF81FBB58293FF54F860" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">O. pentactis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, five and six-armed specimens can be in the same clade (
<bibRefCitation id="2B154B46534FFF81FD4482B7FBEDF860" author="O'Hara, T. D. &amp; Smith, P. J. &amp; Mills, V. S. &amp; Smirnov, A. V. &amp; Steinke, D." box="[880,1093,1972,1998]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" pagination="321 - 333" refId="ref35087" refString="O'Hara, T. D., Smith, P. J., Mills, V. S., Smirnov, A. V. &amp; Steinke, D. (2013) Biogeographical and phylogeographical relationships of the bathyal ophiuroid fauna of the Macquarie Ridge, Southern Ocean. Polar Biology, 36, 321 - 333. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / s 00300 - 012 - 1261 - 9" type="journal article" year="2013">
O’Hara 
<emphasis id="7DF0EAA5534FFF81FDFF82B6FBAAF860" box="[971,1026,1972,1998]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">et al.</emphasis>
2013
</bibRefCitation>
). However, in this instance, the 
<typeStatus id="903F8815534FFF81FEA382DBFF51F85C" box="[151,249,2008,2034]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName id="88844D34534FFF81FF1482DBFE07F85C" authorityName="Lyman" authorityYear="1878" box="[288,431,2008,2034]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiacanthidae" genus="Ophiacantha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiacanthida" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="cuspidata">
<emphasis id="7DF0EAA5534FFF81FF1482DBFE07F85C" box="[288,431,2008,2034]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">O. cuspidata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry id="37937627534FFF81FFC782DBFD1CF85C" box="[499,692,2008,2034]" name="Ascension Island" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Ascension Island</collectingCountry>
in the South Atlantic appears to be distinct from other five-armed specimens from the North Atlantic that are close to 
<taxonomicName id="88844D34534DFF83FCE78594FCFFFF1F" authorityName="Sars" authorityYear="1872" box="[723,855,151,177]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiacanthidae" genus="Ophiacantha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiacanthida" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="anomala">
<emphasis id="7DF0EAA5534DFF83FCE78594FCFFFF1F" box="[723,855,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">O. anomala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see 
<bibRefCitation id="2B154B46534DFF83FDA48594FB78FF1F" author="Martynov, A. V. &amp; Litvinova, N. M." box="[912,1232,151,177]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" pagination="76 - 111" refId="ref33866" refString="Martynov, A. V. &amp; Litvinova, N. M. (2008) Deep-water Ophiuroidea of the northern Atlantic with descriptions of three new species and taxonomic remarks on certain genera and species. Marine Biology Research, 4, 76 - 111. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 17451000701840066" type="journal article" year="2008">Martynov &amp; Litvinova 2008</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 7C). The disc spines on the five- and six-armed 
<taxonomicName id="88844D34534DFF83FC2C85B8FD35FF7B" authorityName="Sars" authorityYear="1872" box="[536,669,187,213]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiacanthidae" genus="Ophiacantha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiacanthida" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="anomala">
<emphasis id="7DF0EAA5534DFF83FC2C85B8FD35FF7B" box="[536,669,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">O. anomala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are shorter and stouter (see 
<bibRefCitation id="2B154B46534DFF83FDE985B8FA89FF7B" author="Martynov, A. V. &amp; Litvinova, N. M." box="[989,1313,187,213]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" pagination="76 - 111" refId="ref33866" refString="Martynov, A. V. &amp; Litvinova, N. M. (2008) Deep-water Ophiuroidea of the northern Atlantic with descriptions of three new species and taxonomic remarks on certain genera and species. Marine Biology Research, 4, 76 - 111. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 17451000701840066" type="journal article" year="2008">Martynov &amp; Litvinova 2008</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 7H–I; 
<bibRefCitation id="2B154B46534DFF83FEA385DCFEF4FF57" author="Mortensen, T." box="[151,348,223,249]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" pagination="1 - 120" refId="ref34437" refString="Mortensen, T. (1933 c) Ophiuroidea. The Danish Ingolf Expedition, 4, 1 - 120, 3 pls." type="journal article" year="1933">Mortensen 1933c</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 18c) than shown for 
<taxonomicName id="88844D34534DFF83FC4985DCFCA4FF57" authorityName="Lyman" authorityYear="1878" box="[637,780,223,249]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiacanthidae" genus="Ophiacantha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiacanthida" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="cuspidata">
<emphasis id="7DF0EAA5534DFF83FC4985DCFCA4FF57" box="[637,780,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">O. cuspidata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and here we recognise the latter as a distinct species.
</paragraph>
